What is a Full Migration?

Use this type of migration for "big bang" (single pass) migrations, or following an earlier pre-stage migration. Use this type of migration after MX record cutover, to make sure you are not missing any data.

  What are the different migration types?

What are the descriptions of the different migration types?

Answer:

1. Trial migration

A trial migration will migrate a very small amount of data in order to test that your project has been created properly and that the mailboxes have been entered correctly. It is completely free and you can perform an unlimited number of trial migrations. Each trial migration will perform the following:

  • It will verify credentials at the source and destination.
  • It will re-create the entire folder hierarchy on the destination, based on what is defined at the source.
  • It will migrate a few sample items in some folders. It will migrate up to 5 items in each folder and up to a total of 10MB in size, in terms of size of total data migrated.

2. Pre Stage migration

A pre-stage migration pre fills a destination mailbox with migrated items, as defined by the pre stage migration settings chosen. A pre stage migration is typically part of a multi-pass migration strategy. It occurs before your MX record cutover and is a great way to pre-fill the majority of the end users' data into their future destination mailboxes whilst they are still using their old email system. It has no impact on the end users' and is a highly recommended strategy to follow since the majority of data is migrated over prior to MX record cutover. Typically only mail items older than 3 months are included in the pre stage migration because these items are unlikely to change.

When performing a pre stage migration it is important to understand that MigrationWiz is a migration solution and not a synchronization solution. With this in mind, it will not propagate updates, deletes or moves of the items previously migrated in the first migration pass because we do not have live monitoring of changes (as with a sync agent) and we cannot handle scenarios such as conflict resolution without user interaction.

Here is what would happen after a delta pass, if items previously migrated to destination have been:

  • Deleted at source: then destination will keep containing these deleted items. We cannot propagate deletes (e.g. if an item is archived at the source, it will look like a delete and we cant delete the item at the destination).
  • Moved from folder A to another folder B: then these items will be duplicated at destination, they will be both in folder A and in folder B at destination.
  • Updated at source: then these items will not be updated at destination. There is no process by which the calendars, contacts, tasks, etc. can be updated. This would require conflict resolution which is only possible with a synchronization solution.

Instead, MigrationWiz watermarks all migrated items so as to avoid re-migrating any items in subsequent passes.

This multi-pass migration strategy typically follows an order of events similar to this:

  • 1st pass (pre stage): Migrate ONLY mail items that are older than 3 months. Performed 1 to 2 weeks before MX record cutover (times vary dependant upon number of mailboxes being migrated and size of mailboxes).
  • Perform MX record cutover
  • 2nd pass (delta): migrate ALL items, with no date filters. Performed after TTL expires.

Note: changing MX records in DNS to point to the new system is not effective immediately and is subject to replication delays. You will have to wait for the TTL (aka Time To Live) to expire (- until then, email systems on the internet may continue to deliver to your old system).

  • Optional 3rd pass (delta): migrate ALL items, with no date filters. Performed 2 or 3 days after MX record cutover. This picks up any residual mail that was still delivered to the old mail system after MX record cutover due to slow DNS internet propagation.

3. Full/Delta migration

Both full and delta migrations have the same settings in MigrationWiz. With both migration types you are performing a migration with no date filters and all items are migrated.

  • With a full migration, you would be migrating everything in one pass. I.e. a single pass migration (Big Bang) strategy will move the entire mailbox in one pass, after MX records are cut-over. A typical scenario consists in cutting over on a Friday evening and migrating during the weekend.
  • With a delta migration, you would be performing this after a pre stage migration, and it is part of a multi pass migration strategy. A delta migration pass allows you to resubmit a mailbox/mailboxes so as to perform a differential migration pass. MigrationWiz will automatically find items that haven't yet been migrated since the first pass, and migrate only those. In other words, a delta pass will find and migrate residual items. In most cases, a delta pass will complete much faster than the initial pass. In a delta pass, MigrationWiz will continue the migration from where it left off and cause no duplicates to be created at the destination - which means that all items which were not migrated in the first pass or were created after/during the first pass, will be migrated.

 4. Retry errors

This will perform another attempt to migrate any items that previously failed to migrate - it will not migrate any previously successfully migrated items.

It will not consume any more licenses.

You may only submit mailboxes in this mode if they satisfy both of the following conditions:

  • The last migration completed successfully.
  • The mailbox contains at least one error.

5. Verify credentials

This will check the credentials for migration at both the source and destination. Verifying credentials will not migrate any data nor consume any licenses.

This will perform the following actions:

  • Check that the mailbox exists on the source.
  • If using admin credentials at the source (- these are entered when creating your project), then verify those credentials.
  • If not using admin credentials at the source and instead entering passwords for each mailbox, then verify those credentials.
  • Check that the mailbox exists on the destination.
  • If using admin credentials at the destination (- these are entered when creating your project), then verify those credentials.
  • If not using admin credentials at the destination and instead entering passwords for each mailbox, then verify those credentials.
